📊 UK Subsidy Data Analysis¶

This project explores and analyses the UK Subsidy Award and Scheme datasets with a focus on transparency, policy relevance, and data-driven insights. The work is grounded in thorough data cleaning, transformation, and exploratory data analysis (EDA), using Python and pandas to uncover patterns in how public subsidies have been distributed across sectors, regions, and time.

Key areas of analysis include:

  • Trends in subsidy amounts and counts over time, especially during the COVID-19 interim period (2021–2023)
  • Breakdown of subsidies by purpose (simplified_category), recipient size, and form
  • Identification of outliers and anomalies in award values
  • Reproduction of key statistics from official government reports
  • Visual summaries such as area plots, heatmaps, and word clouds to communicate findings clearly

The notebook is designed to be reproducible and well-documented, making it a useful reference for analysts, researchers, and anyone interested in UK public finance and subsidy transparency.

📁 Data Source: UK Government Subsidy Transparency Database

#Cleaning up the data types and datetimes

def clean_data_types(df):
    for col, dtype in dtype_mapping.items():
        if col in df.columns:
            if dtype.startswith('datetime'):
                df[col] = pd.to_datetime(df[col], errors='coerce')
            else:
                df[col] = df[col].astype(dtype, errors='ignore')
    return df

authority_stats = non_zero_amount.groupby('authority_name')['amount_full'].agg(['mean', 'count'])

#It would be too difficult to visualise all so focussing on top 20

# Focus on top 20 authorities by number of awards
top_authorities = authority_stats.sort_values(by='count', ascending=False).head(20)

# Sort by average amount in descending order
top_authorities = top_authorities.sort_values(by='mean', ascending=False)



plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
ax = sns.barplot(x=top_authorities['mean'], y=top_authorities.index, palette='mako')

for i, (value, name) in enumerate(zip(top_authorities['mean'], top_authorities.index)):
    ax.text(value, i, f'{value:,.0f}', va='center', ha='left', fontsize=9)

plt.title('Average Subsidy Amount by Top 20 Authorities (Descending Order)')
plt.xlabel('Average Amount (£)')
plt.ylabel('Authority Name')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import re

def normalize_and_categorize(subsidy_purpose):
    # Normalize text
    text = subsidy_purpose.lower().strip()
    text = re.sub(r"other\s*-\s*", "", text)
    text = re.sub(r"\s+", " ", text)

    # Keyword-based categorization
    categories = {
        'culture': 'Culture and Heritage',
        'heritage': 'Culture and Heritage',
        'employment': 'Employment',
        'training': 'Training and Skills',
        'skills': 'Training and Skills',
        'infrastructure': 'Infrastructure',
        'research': 'Research and Development',
        'development': 'Research and Development',
        'environmental': 'Environment',
        'energy': 'Energy and Efficiency',
        'efficiency': 'Energy and Efficiency',
        'housing': 'Housing',
        'welsh': 'Welsh Language Promotion',
        'language': 'Welsh Language Promotion',
        'sme': 'SME Support',
        'business': 'Business Support',
        'community': 'Community Support',
        'health': 'Health and Social Care',
        'social': 'Health and Social Care',
        'education': 'Education',
        'sport': 'Sports and Leisure',
        'leisure': 'Sports and Leisure',
        'transport': 'Transport',
        'public': 'Public Services',
        'volunteer': 'Volunteering and Social Action',
        'child': 'Childcare and Family Support',
        'family': 'Childcare and Family Support',
        'addiction': 'Addiction Support',
        'mental': 'Mental Health Support',
        'innovation': 'Innovation and Technology',
        'digital': 'Digital Inclusion',
        'tourism': 'Tourism and Visitor Economy',
        'rate': 'Business Rates Relief',
        'real estate': 'Real Estate and Property',
        'construction': 'Construction',
        'manufacturing': 'Manufacturing',
        'science': 'Science and Technology',
        'vulnerable': 'Support for Vulnerable Groups',
        'carer': 'Support for Vulnerable Groups',
        'covid': 'COVID-19 Support',
        'pandemic': 'COVID-19 Support',
        'airport': 'Transport',
        'bus': 'Transport',
        'rail': 'Transport',
        'green': 'Environment',
        'waste': 'Environment',
        'renewable': 'Energy and Efficiency',
        'decarbon': 'Energy and Efficiency',
        'local': 'Local Development',
        'visitor': 'Tourism and Visitor Economy',
        'voluntary': 'Volunteering and Social Action',
        'enterprise': 'Business Support',
        'rescue': 'Rescue Aid',
        'aid': 'Rescue Aid',
    }

    for keyword, category in categories.items():
        if keyword in text:
            return category
    return "Other"

def clean_subsidy_form(value):
    if pd.isna(value):
        return 'Other'
    val = value.strip().lower()

    if 'grant' in val:
        return 'Grant'
    elif 'loan' in val:
        return 'Loan'
    elif 'equity' in val:
        return 'Equity'
    elif 'guarantee' in val:
        return 'Guarantee'
    elif 'rate relief' in val or 'business rates relief' in val:
        return 'Rate Relief'
    elif 'contract' in val:
        return 'Contract'
    elif 'goods or services' in val or 'discount' in val or 'below market' in val:
        return 'Goods/Services Discount'
    else:
        return 'Other'

Comments

  • Dataset requires cleaning and standardisation - which can alter results depending on how extensively this is done
  • Missing complete data on subsidy type and description
  • Varying plots above show the proportion of total amounts and average subsidy value is highest for subsidies around infrastructure, energy investment etc
  • SMEs recieve greatest attention followed by large firms (> 250)
  • Out of streamlined subsidies, R&D takes up overwhelming majority -> is there future room to develop the other 2, do they need combining or a creation of a new one?
  • Standardisation of answers is becoming enforced and so repeating this analysis in the near future should prove easier and rewarding
  • It should then become easier to utilise machine learning algorithms such as clustering to get a better idea of how different subsidies work and are potentially interlinked
